  "prompt": "What is the appropriate way to use Ms., Mrs., and Miss?",
  "response": "Here's a guide to using these titles:\n\n1. Ms. (pronounced \"miz\")\n- Used for adult women, regardless of marital status\n- Preferred in professional settings\n- Does not indicate whether a woman is married or single\n- Most neutral and respectful option in modern usage\n\n2. Mrs. (pronounced \"misses\")\n- Traditionally used for married women\n- Followed by her husband's last name (e.g., Mrs. John Smith)\n- Less commonly used in professional settings today\n- Indicates marital status\n\n3. Miss\n- Traditionally used for unmarried women\n- Typically used for younger, single women\n- Less preferred in professional settings\n- Indicates marital status\n\nGeneral guidelines:\n- When in doubt, use \"Ms.\"\n- Ask the person how they prefer to be addressed\n- In professional contexts, \"Ms.\" is generally the most appropriate\n- Some women have personal preferences about titles\n- Increasingly, many women prefer being addressed by their first name in casual settings\n\nWhen writing formal correspondence, use the title the person prefers or has indicated.",
